[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "fruity breath",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "really thirsty and confused",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "deep heavy breathing",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "urgency": "call_911",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "applies_to_conditions":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ["type_1_diabetes", "type_2_diabetes"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The substring `"really thirsty and confused"` is a low-frequency phrase but coaching conversations span months and accumulate a lot of patient text. Patients with diabetes may say things like "I was really thirsty and confused about whether to take my pill at lunch or dinner" — the substring matches but the acuity is wrong. Similarly `"deep heavy breathing"` could match a yoga or relaxation discussion ("I was practicing deep heavy breathing during the panic attack"), and `"can't stop vomiting"` could match a family-history mention ("my husband can't stop vomiting after the procedure").
